attributes.description: Consul in 54 BCE. Chosen to succeed Caesar in Gaul and fought him at Corfinum. Brother-in-law of Cato the Younger.
Consul in 62. Accused of electoral bribery and defended by Cicero. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucius_Licinius_Murena_(consul_62_BC)
Sister of Clodius, wife of Lucullus.
General and politician. Rival of Pompey.
A Greek recipient of Cicero's letters.
Led Pompey's soldiers in Spain. Died at the Battle of Munda.
Accused of parricide for killing his father under Sulla's proscriptions. Defended by Cicero. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sextus_Roscius
A man in training to be a lawyer, insulted by Cicero in court.
Consul in 62, led the debate against Lentulus Sura and Cethegus after being elected to the consulship. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decimus_Junius_Silanus_(consul)
Aided Cicero's investigation into Catiline's conspiracy.
Wife of Cicero. Came from a wealthy family and funded Cicero's early career. Divorced after the civil war. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terentia
Dominant political figure. Protg of Sulla. Successful general and political networker. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pompey
A member of Catiline's conspiracy. He remained in Rome with Lentulus Sura. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaius_Cornelius_Cethegus_(conspirator)
This appears to be a mistake by Plutarch, Cicero names L. Vargunteius as his would-be assassin but Plutarch uses the name Marcius.
Appointed by Cicero to lead against the Catilinarian Conspiracy outside of Rome. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quintus_Caecilius_Metellus_Celer
Greek rhetorician. Rebuked by Cicero in a lost letter.
A strong supporter of Caesar's. Became a triumvir under the Lex Titia. Ruled the eastern half of the empire before falling into war with Octavian.
Close friend and father-in-law of Caesar. Ensured Caesar's legislation was protected after his consulship ended.
Supported Cicero's retoration. Husband of Tullia.
Pompeian officer. Two sons-in-law had been exiled.
Accomplished general and politician. Became dictator during civil war with Pompey.
Friend of Cicero and Pompey. A Speech in his defense survives.
Rival of Cicero's who eventually supported his restoration.
Leader of Caesar's assassins. Died at the Battle of Philippi.

nodes.label: L. Caecilius Metellus C. f. Q. n.

attributes.description: Successful politician. Held the censorship in 64 BCE.
Consul in 44 and strong supporter of Caesar. Known as an ambitious and popular politician.
Mistress of Q. Curtius. Informer for Cicero against the Catilinarian Conspiracy.
Greek rhetorician. Received Roman citizenship from Caesar.
Defended by Cicero then prosecuted Cicero's friend Sabinus.
Catiliarian sympathizer. Worked against Cicero after Cicero's consulship ended.
Brother of Cicero. Successful politician in his own right. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quintus_Tullius_Cicero
Friend of Cicero's. Prevented from supporting Cicero in exile.
Friend of Cicero's. Supported Pompey's side against Caesar while in Italy.
Disgraced Roman politician. Prosecuted for misgovernment in Sicily by Cicero in 70 BCE. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaius_Verres
Senator, may have decended from slaves.
A slave and freedman of Cicero's. He maintained Cicero's writings and later published his letters.
Son of Scipio Nasica, adopted by Metellus Pius. Supported Pompey in the civil war, leading the African army. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quintus_Caecilius_Metellus_Pius_Scipio
Caesar's wife. Accused of adultery with Clodius. Not related to Pompey.
A military tribune serving under Caesar.
Violent and aggressive politician. Rival to Clodius.
Cicero's colleague as consul in 63 BCE. Led the army against Catiline's rebellion. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaius_Antonius_Hybrida
Rhetoric teacher. Beloved by Metellus Nepos.
Dominant politician. Used wealth to fund political campaigns and network. Rival of Pompey. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marcus_Licinius_Crassus
Defended by Cicero. Accused by Munatius
Sister of Clodius, wife of Marcius Rex.
Partisan of Pompey, led an illegal military expedition in Egypt to restore Ptolemy Auletes to power.
Anti-Caesar. Worked to maintain good governance in the late republic.
Praetor in 63 BCE. Found the cache of waepons held by Cethegus.
Politician, supported the first triumvirate at tribune of the plebs in 59 BCE. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Publius_Vatinius
Poitician. Removed from the Senate in 70 BCE for immorality. Elected praetor in 63. Leader of Catiline's conspiracy in Rome. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Publius_Cornelius_Lentulus_Sura
Orator. Represented the city of Adramyttium in Rome during the Mithridatic Wars
Orator. Taught both Cicero and Caesar. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apollonius_Molon
Uncertain. May be the consul of 66.
Freedman of Sulla, purchased the property of Sex. Roscius Amerinus. Accused Sex. Roscius of parricide. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucius_Cornelius_Chrysogonus
Conspired to assassinate Caesar. Possibly proscribed in 43 BCE.
A powerful politician who held a dictatorship from 80-75 BCE after wars against Marius and Cinna. He enacted major reforms of the political system which defined the politics of the late Republic.
Leader of Caesar's assassins. Died at the Battle of Philippi.
Double-crossed Pharnaces in war against Caesar
Prefect of engineers at Pompey's camp in Macedonia.
A magistrate with imperium serving under Pompey.
Respected orator, lawyer and politician in the late Republic. Supported the Optimates. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quintus_Hortensius
Son of the dictator. Executed by Caesar.
Member of Caesar's expedition to Gades
Disgraced Roman politician. Unable to attain the consulship. Accused of assassination attempts and leader of a rebellion n 63 BCE. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catiline

One of the most prolific authors of antiquity and an influential politician in the late Republic. He was a supporter of Pompey's but they fell out after Caesar's consulship and Cicero was exiled by the tribune Clodius. Pompey later helped restore Cicero. Cicero survived the Civil War and the assassination of Caesar and took up the cause against Antony. For that he was killed by the Second Triumvirate.
An officer in Sulla's armies and leader of Catiline's rebellious army.
Aggressive politician. Rival of Cicero and Pompey. Supported popular policies as tribune in 58 BCE.
Son of Pompey the Great. Fought Caesar in Spain but maintained rebellion against Caesar and Triumvirs untile 35 BCE.

nodes.label: Cn. Domitius Ahenobarbus f. L. n. Cn.

attributes.description: Consul in 68 BCE, proconsul of Cilicia in the Mithridatic War
Sister of Clodius, mistress of Caelius Rufus and Catullus.
Emement senator. Worked against Caesar and Pompey but likely died before or during Caesar's consulship.
Politician. Supported Pompey in the civil war. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marcus_Claudius_Marcellus_(consul_51_BC)
